# Load data
kl_data <- read_csv("s2-kl-smooth-joined.csv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c('X', 'Y'), crs = 32608) %>%
  group_by(id) %>%
  filter(row_number() == 7) %>%
  ungroup()

Data overview

The data set consist of the center coordinates for 660 pixels arranged in a grid. Each pixel is 10 m x 10 m. The cooridnates are projected in UTM zone 8N (a planar metric projection), distances are in m.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = st_geometry(kl_data), col = "red") +
  geom_sf(data = st_geometry(kl_data) %>% st_buffer(5, endCapStyle = "SQUARE"),
          fill = NA) +
  theme_map()

Each pixel has two attributes of interest:

  1. peak-seasons greenness (NDVI)
plot_grid(
  ggplot(st_drop_geometry(kl_data)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(x = ndvi.max), binwidth = 0.01) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0.3, 0.7, 0.05)) +
    theme_cowplot(),
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = kl_data, mapping = aes(colour = ndvi.max)) +
    scale_colour_continuous_sequential(palette = "viridis", rev = F,
                                       limits = c(0.35, 0.75)) +
    theme_map(),
  labels = c("a) ndvi distribution", "b) ndvi in space"),
  hjust = 0,
  scale = 0.9,
  ncol = 1,
  nrow = 2
)

  1. snow persistence across the season (snow.auc)
plot_grid(
  ggplot(st_drop_geometry(kl_data)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(x = snow.auc), binwidth = 1) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 12, 1)) +
    theme_cowplot(),
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = kl_data, mapping = aes(colour = snow.auc)) +
    scale_colour_continuous_sequential(rev = F,
                                       limits = c(0,12)) +
    theme_map(),
  labels = c("a) snow.auc distribution", "b) snow.auc in space"),
  hjust = 0,
  scale = 0.9,
  ncol = 1,
  nrow = 2
)

Hypothesis

We predict that a higher snow presistance (snow.auc) is associated with a lower peak season greenness (ndvi.max):

ndvi.max ~ (-a) * snow.auc + c

Here is a simple linear model fit:

kl_lm <- lm(ndvi.max ~ snow.auc, data = kl_data)
tidy(kl_lm)
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)  0.531     0.00197    270.   0       
## 2 snow.auc    -0.00542   0.00144     -3.76 0.000185
ggplot(kl_data, aes(x = snow.auc, y = ndvi.max)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(x = snow.auc, y = fitted(kl_lm)), colour = "blue")  +
  annotate("text", x = 12, y = 0.65, hjust = 1, vjust = 1, 
           label = "predictions in blue") +
  theme_cowplot()

However, we know that there are many other factors that are influencing peak season greenness (ndvi.max), for example nutrient clusters etc We havent measured these, but they are also not of interest to us.We therefore chose a spatial error model to account for them implicitly and to avoid pseudo replication.

Spatial autocoreelation in the response variable

Here is a variogram for the ndv.max and the residuals for the linera model with a spherical model fitted.

# Fit variogram ndvi
vario_ndvi.max <- as_Spatial(kl_data) %>% as("SpatialPointsDataFrame") %>%
  variogram(ndvi.max ~ 1, data = ., cutoff = 130, width = 10)
vario_ndvi.max_fit <- fit.variogram(vario_ndvi.max, model = vgm(model = "Sph")) 
# Fit variogram residuals
vario_resid <- kl_data %>% mutate(resid = kl_lm$residuals) %>%
  as_Spatial() %>% 
  as("SpatialPointsDataFrame") %>%
  variogram(resid ~ 1, data = ., cutoff = 130, width = 10)
vario_resid_fit <- fit.variogram(vario_resid, model = vgm(model = "Sph")) 

# Visualise results
plot_grid(
ggplot(vario_ndvi.max) +
  geom_point(aes(x = dist, y = gamma)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = dist, y = gamma), 
            data = variogramLine(vario_ndvi.max_fit, 
                                 dist_vector = seq(10,130,10))) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = vario_ndvi.max_fit$range) +
  annotate("text", x = vario_ndvi.max_fit$range, y  = Inf, 
           label = paste0(" range = ", round(vario_ndvi.max_fit$range, 1), " m"),
           hjust = 0, vjust = 1.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(10, 130), breaks = seq(10,130,10)) +
  labs(x = "lag distance (m)", y = "semivariance (gamma)") +
  theme_cowplot(),
ggplot(vario_resid) +
  geom_point(aes(x = dist, y = gamma)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = dist, y = gamma), 
            data = variogramLine(vario_resid_fit, 
                                 dist_vector = seq(10,130,10))) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = vario_resid_fit$range) +
  annotate("text", x = vario_resid_fit$range, y  = Inf, 
           label = paste0(" range = ", round(vario_resid_fit$range, 1), " m"),
           hjust = 0, vjust = 1.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(10, 130), breaks = seq(10,130,10)) +
  labs(x = "lag distance (m)", y = "semivariance (gamma)") +

  hjust = 0,
  scale = 0.9,
  nrow = 2,
  ncol = 1
)

Arguably, the both fits are a bit crude as the data does not seem to fully level off beyond the largest lag distance assessed (130 m = 1/3 of diagonal of dataset). However,the range of 87 m (90 m) provides a good starting point for the choice of the neighbourhood size.

To further inform the choice of the neighbourhood size, we caluclated Morans I for the same lag distances as shown in the variogram (here upper ends of neighbourhood).

morans_i <- seq(10, 130, 10) %>%
  pblapply(function(x){
    kl_nb <- dnearneigh(kl_data, d1 = 0, d2 = x)
    kl_lb <- nb2listw(kl_nb, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)
    moran <- moran.mc(kl_lm$residuals, kl_lb, nsim = 999, zero.policy = TRUE)
    data.frame(dist = x,
               morans_i = moran$statistic)
  }) %>%
  bind_rows()
ggplot(data = morans_i, aes(x = dist, y = morans_i)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 90, linetype = "dashed") +
  annotate("text", x = 90, y = Inf, label = " variogram range ~ 90 m",
           hjust = 0, vjust = 2) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = morans_i[morans_i$dist == 90,"morans_i"]) +
  annotate("text", x = 10, y = morans_i[morans_i$dist == 90,"morans_i"],
           label = paste0("Closest Moran's I to varigoram range = ",
                          round(morans_i[morans_i$dist == 90,"morans_i"],2)),
           hjust = 0, vjust = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(10,130), breaks = seq(10,130,10)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1), breaks = seq(0,1,0.1)) +
  labs(x = "Uppder neighbourhood distance (m)",
       y = "Moran's I", 
       title = "Moran's I for residuals lm(ndvi.max ~ snow.auc)") +
  theme_cowplot()

A Morans I value for varigoram range of 0.38 seems like a reasonable value, suggesting that there is a moderate level of autocorrelation at this neighborhood distance.

Lets visualise the residuals in space with a 90 m neigbhourhood as a reference:

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = kl_data %>% mutate(resid = kl_lm$residuals),
          aes(colour = resid)) +
  geom_sf(data = kl_data %>% 
                        summarize() %>%
                        st_centroid() %>%
                        st_buffer(90), fill = NA) +
  scale_color_continuous_sequential(palette = "plasma") +
  theme_map()

The neighbourhood seems rather large, but hen it also seems to match the concentration of residuals on the lefthand side, where there would be a high reisk of pesudo- replication.

Fitting a spatial error model with a 90 m neighbourhood

We fit a simple spatial error model using the errorsarlm() function from the spatialreg package.

# Define neighbourhood 90
kl_lw <- dnearneigh(kl_data, d1 = 0, d2 = 90) %>%
  nb2listw(style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE) 
# Fit model 
kl_sem <- errorsarlm(ndvi.max ~ snow.auc, 
                            data = kl_data, 
                            listw = kl_lw, 
                            zero.policy = TRUE)

Model coefficients

# Summary
tidy(kl_sem) %>% kbl() %>% kable_classic(full_width = F, html_font = "Cambria")
term estimate std.error statistic p.value
(Intercept) 0.5070479 0.0615985 8.231493 0
snow.auc -0.0092349 0.0011494 -8.034585 0
lambda 0.9767295 0.0159619 61.191407 0

Model statistics

# Summary
glance(kl_sem) %>% kbl() %>% kable_classic(full_width = F, html_font = "Cambria")
r.squared AIC BIC deviance logLik nobs
0.4382793 -2467.127 -2449.158 0.8939786 1237.564 660

Compare to AIC of simple linear model (no spatial error): -2119.4334754.

The AIC of the spatial error model is lower, suggesting that it provides a better fit.

Spatial error model vis

ggplot(kl_data %>% mutate(fit = fitted(kl_sem))) +
  geom_point(aes(x = snow.auc, y = ndvi.max), alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_point(aes(x = snow.auc, y = fit), colour = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  annotate("text", x = 12, y = 0.65, hjust = 1, vjust = 1, 
           label = "fit in blue") +
    theme_cowplot()
## This method assumes the response is known - see manual page

The spatial error models seems to produce two groupings in the data based on the intercept, this seems logical, considering the distribution of residuals and neighbourhoods size as discussed earlier (see spatial figure). Lets see whether there is still auto correlation in the residuals of the sem.

Morans I for 90 m neigbhourhoods:

moran.mc(kl_sem$residuals, kl_lw, nsim = 999, zero.policy = TRUE)
## 
##  Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I

## weights: kl_lw  
## number of simulations + 1: 1000 
## 
## statistic = -0.00080648, observed rank = 628, p-value = 0.372
## alternative hypothesis: greater

The spatial error model seems to have successfully accounted for the auto correlation at the chosen neighbourhood size.

Again the model seems to be capturing the spatial autocorellation and perhaps, even better than the 90 m neighbourhood mpdel, but some residual autocorellation remains in the residuals.

Eye-balling the variogram and residual in space plot it seems like that this autocorellation seems to be highest at around a 30 m distance (Morans I 0.4, and semivariance reaches sill).

Lets have a a look at that:

Check Hausman test

(Does the spatial error model make more sense than the normal linear model):

Hausman.test(kl_sem_30)
## 
##  Spatial Hausman test (asymptotic)
## 
## data:  NULL
## Hausman test = -9.7898, df = 2, p-value = 0.007485

The test is significant (p <= 0.05), suggesting that neither the OLS or the SEM are a good choice. However, I think the latter makes more sense.

Final plot of the 30 m model

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = snow.auc, y = ndvi.max), alpha = 0.5, 
             data = kl_data %>% mutate(fit = fitted(kl_sem_30))) +
  geom_point(aes(x = snow.auc, y = fit), colour = "blue", alpha = 0.5,
             data = kl_data %>% mutate(fit = fitted(kl_sem_30))) +
  geom_line(aes(x = 0:12, y = kl_sem_30$coefficients[1] + (0:12 * kl_sem_30$coefficients[2])),
            col = "blue") +
  annotate("text", x = 12, y = 0.65, hjust = 1, vjust = 1, 
           label = "fit & predictions in blue") +
    theme_cowplot()
